Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He hated it above all because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his squad. Quietly he got up from his bunk, put on his combat suit, threw his body armor over, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, taking particular care with a certain small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. Hanging from it was everything he needed, such as his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, sludge and ice crunched under his boots.
He took out a lighter from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short drag before opening the door slightly. In the last week, he had to think of quite a few ways to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset wake-up alarm, because it usually didn't work at all and only produced a faint noise from the speakers.
"Wake them up?" Cohren turned around and saw Squad Leader Nemic approaching him.
"Ja," answered Cohren.
"With what do you want to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came toward him already in full uniform.
"Guten Morgen," said Craith.
"Wake up from what?" asked Cohren.
"First of all, we didn't feel like waiting to see what you had in mind for today. And secondly, the shock troops, who are the first to get up, get to choose the morning ration," answered one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Corporal," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a button. A loud, shrill alarm rang out in the barracks. Inside, he heard muffled cursing and people running around.
"Mate, Valturi," said Nemic. "You'd think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
" Well, my men from the training camp have learned," replied Cohren, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the troop and train leaders also know that they have to wake up before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal belongings to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others seemed more irritated.
"Good morning," said Cohren in a good mood.
"Despite all respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?" asked a corporal from the shock troops.
"Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn't sleep," said Cohren.
"Pack everything you need into your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and executive officer of the company, it was his responsibility to oversee and support the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw, in this task. "We are not coming back here. Corporals and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second Shock Troop Division, second army. Before they were merged, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren felt mixed emotions regarding his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first train, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operations base. Most of the lamps had red-tinted glass to avoid detection by enemy bombers. Daybreak had countered Wild Weasel air and ground attacks to combat them.
"Another day and a new task for the Hellhounds," said Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced operations base outside of Ianlos. We will support the ground attack," answered Cohren and took a drag on his cigarette. He gave Craith partial credit for starting to smoke, but a year in the field changes a person, so he said nothing.
"Damn. It's getting worse at the front," muttered Nemic. "All the messages say: 'Support the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan Front.' How about help for the Howland Front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're starting with the first armed column and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should be here already."
"Did Shaw arrange a ride for us?" asked Nemic a bit surprised.
"Yes. He's honestly not as bad as I thought. Although not particularly approachable, you can put up with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and adjusted his backpack in the process. "All units of the Exodus Company will meet at the West Garage when they're ready. We'll depart with the first armed column at 0500."
In split-second intervals, he received responses from the squad leaders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all arrived here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt as if he had known them forever, although it had been no more than two years. They were squad leaders, though Craith had been leading the second column for a week, after its previous leader had been discharged for medical reasons following being shot by a Daybreak sharpshooter.
On the way to the West Garage, Cohren and Nemic spotted a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four infantry tanks. Their crews were running around, ensuring their machines were combat-ready. Quickly, Cohren spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armed column. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came towards them, as always with an expressionless face.
"Lieutenant Nemic… Lieutenant Valturi…" He said, noting that Cohren was slower, while looking at Cohren's pistol holsters and then up again. "I assume the company is ready?"
